They capture this economic category from the various points of view of the fields studied and are of great cognitive importance. However, of greater practical importance, among others for economic policy purposes, are the GATS models, i.e. the model:
- cross-border trade, i.e. transfer of services without movement of service provider and service recipient;
- foreign consumption of services, i.e. movement of the service recipient to the service provider's country;
- commercial presence, i.e., the commercial presence of the service provider in the service recipient's country in the form of a subsidiary, branch or representative office;
- the presence of individuals providing services in the service recipient's country in the form of self-employment, temporary employment or posting.
